{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489144"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:06:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:06:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"602"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/602"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.4,0.09,0.09,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"602"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108033"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"602","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/602"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"602"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90446"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2960"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"301"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4843"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40129"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43021"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108033"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-week history of worsening nausea, vomiting and malaise. She reports vomiting three times yesterday, with the vomitus consisting of semi-digested food. Today, she has noted slightly reduced urine output. She has a medical history of chronic back pain, depression and gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. Her medications include ibuprofen (taken intermittently for five years) and pantoprazole (started one month ago). On examination, she appears unwell with pulse rate 82/min, blood pressure 115/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. She has a diffuse maculopapular rash on her chest and abdomen. The rest of the physical examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EEosinophils: 1.2 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (0.04-0.4)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECreatinine: 250 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUrinalysis: leukocytes +\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUrine sediment: white cell casts\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis","Acute interstitial nephritis","Pre-renal acute kidney injury","IgA vasculitis","Urinary tract infection"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with acute kidney injury, eosinophilia, rash, and systemic symptoms one month after starting pantoprazole, which is highly suggestive of drug-induced acute interstitial nephritis (AIN). The timing is classic, as drug-induced AIN typically occurs around two weeks after commencing the causative medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute interstitial nephritis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis. Proton pump inhibitors are the most common cause of AIN in Australia. The presentation includes nausea, vomiting, and malaise secondary to uraemia, along with the classic triad of fever, rash, and eosinophilia (though all three are present in only 10% of cases). Urinalysis showing white cells and white cell casts strongly supports this diagnosis, as white cell casts are characteristic of interstitial inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs in patients with a history of asthma and allergic rhinitis, presenting with systemic features including fever and weight loss.  The absence of these features makes eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis unlikely. While eosinophilia is common, and 30% have renal involvement, the temporal relationship with pantoprazole initiation also makes this less likely. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPre-renal acute kidney injury\u003C/strong\u003E could be caused by volume depletion from vomiting or NSAID use, but would not explain the eosinophilia and maculopapular rash. Additionally, pre-renal injury typically presents with concentrated urine and would not show white cells or white cell casts on urinalysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgA vasculitis\u003C/strong\u003E (formerly Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura) typically presents with palpable purpura on the lower limbs, abdominal pain, and arthritis. While renal involvement is common, the rash distribution and appearance in this case are not consistent with IgA vasculitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary tract infection\u003C/strong\u003E could cause systemic symptoms and white cells in urine, but would not explain the eosinophilia, rash, or significant acute kidney injury unless complicated by sepsis. Typical urinary symptoms such as dysuria or frequency would be expected, and white cell casts would not be present.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Proton pump inhibitor use is the most common cause of acute interstitial nephritis in Australia.","Acute interstitial nephritis typically presents with nausea, malaise, raised serum creatinine, and may include eosinophilia and rash.","Drug-induced acute interstitial nephritis usually occurs around two weeks after commencing the causative medication."],"references":["Raghavan R, Eknoyan G. Acute interstitial nephritis \u2013 a reappraisal and update. Clinical Nephrology 2-14; 82:149-62."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90446"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"602"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90446"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-05T19:38:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-05T19:41:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"602"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108033"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1984"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddd1\u200d\ud83c\udf3e","name":"Rural \u0026 Remote Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2023-08-28T22:25:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-08-28T22:25:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"2960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2960"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Acute interstitial nephritis","synonyms":["AIN"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-08-28T20:44:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-28T20:44:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4964"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Gastrointestinal Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"22"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4969"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Kidney and Urinary Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"22"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11625"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Adult I